"""
MKT Original — Leviticus chapters 26–27
Run: python3 scripts/zc-original-leviticus-26-27.py
ch26 (46 verses): covenant blessings, curses, exile and restoration — the Holiness Code's climax
ch27 (34 verses): vows, valuations, dedicated things, tithes
Key terms: keri (perversity/hostility), cherem (irrevocable devotion), erekh (valuation),
           neder (vow), ga'al (redeem), ma'aser (tithe), zecharti berit (covenant remembrance)
"""
import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists(): return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing: existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]: existing[ch][v] = html

new_entries = {
"26": {
"1": "<p><strong>lo taasu lachem elilim</strong>: you shall not make for yourselves idols (<em>elilim</em>). The Holiness Code's climax (ch. 26) opens with a prohibition on idolatry. <strong>Elilim</strong> (from <em>el</em> = god, but diminutive/pejorative — worthless things, nothings) is distinct from <em>pesel</em> (carved image) or <em>asherah</em> (fertility pole). The placement of this prohibition at the head of the covenant consequence chapter signals that idolatry is the fundamental covenant violation — the root cause of all the curses that follow. <strong>Pesel</strong> (carved idol) and <strong>matsevah</strong> (standing pillar) are also prohibited, along with bowing down to any figured stone (<em>even maskiyt</em>). The triple prohibition covers the full range of idolatrous worship forms.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>shabbetotai tishmoru umikdashi tirau</strong>: you shall keep my Sabbaths and reverence my sanctuary. The Sabbath command and sanctuary reverence close the prohibition section and immediately precede the covenant consequences. The bracketing of the covenant laws with Sabbath (the time-marker) and sanctuary (the space-marker) emphasizes that covenant faithfulness is expressed in both temporal and spatial dimensions — how Israel orders its time and how it treats God's dwelling place. The double command provides the positive foundation for what follows: if these are kept, blessing follows; if violated, curse.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>im bechukotai telechu</strong>: if you walk (<em>telechu</em>, from <em>halak</em>) in my statutes. The conditional structure of the covenant blessings opens with the most comprehensive formulation: walking (<em>halak</em>) in the statutes. <strong>Halak</strong> as a covenantal term describes the ongoing movement of a life — not one-time decisions but the habitual direction of daily conduct. <strong>Chukotai</strong> (my statutes, from <em>chaq</em> = to engrave, to inscribe) — the statutes are inscribed by divine authority, not negotiated. The conditional if establishes the covenant as a bilateral relationship: YHWH's blessings are real but not unconditional.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>venatatai geshmeihem beitam</strong>: I will give your rains in their season (<em>beitam</em> = at their proper time). The first blessing is agricultural: seasonal rain. In the ANE, rain at the right time was the primary indicator of divine favor — drought signaled divine disfavor. The connection between covenant faithfulness and agricultural fertility is not primitive causalism but covenant theology: the land is part of the covenant gift, and its fruitfulness is tied to the covenant relationship. The Deuteronomic parallels (Deut 11:14; 28:12) confirm this is standard covenant framework, not coincidental correlation.</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>vehissig lachem dayish et-batzir uvatzir yassig et-zara</strong>: the threshing shall last until the harvest, and the harvest until sowing. Abundant harvest is described as continuous: one season's work overlaps the next because the yield is so great. This hyperbolic abundance is the covenant blessing imagination at full stretch — not just enough but overflowing. The image reverses Amos 9:13 (eschatological restoration) and is fulfilled in the new creation's abundance.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>venatatai shalom baaretz</strong>: I will give peace (<em>shalom</em>) in the land. <strong>Shalom</strong> (wholeness, wellbeing, peace) encompasses security from predators, freedom from war, and social harmony — the full flourishing of communal life. The removal of harmful beasts (<em>chayah raah</em>) and the lying-down-in-safety image describe a restored Eden-like condition. <strong>Shalom</strong> is the covenant's comprehensive goal: not merely absence of conflict but the positive flourishing of all that God intended in creation.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>uredeftem et-oiveichem venapelu lifneichem lacherev</strong>: you shall pursue your enemies and they shall fall before you by the sword. Military victory as covenant blessing — not aggression but the ability to defend and prevail. The pursuit (<em>radaf</em>) rather than mere resistance implies initiative: the covenant community does not merely hold its ground but advances when threatened.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>vechamisha mikem yirdfu meah umeah mikem revavah yirdofu</strong>: five of you shall chase a hundred, and a hundred of you shall chase ten thousand. The asymmetric military blessing — disproportionate victory — is a hallmark of divine warfare theology. The exponential ratio (5:100 then 100:10,000 = 20:1 then 100:1) describes not just success but overwhelming, miraculous victory. Gideon's 300 against 135,000 (Judg 7-8) is the classic narrative fulfillment of this promise.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>uphariti etchem vehirbeti etchem</strong>: I will turn to you and make you fruitful and multiply you. <strong>Panah</strong> (to turn to, face toward) — YHWH's face/attention directed toward Israel is the source of all blessing. The fruitfulness and multiplication echo the Adamic and Abrahamic promises (Gen 1:28; 17:6) — covenant faithfulness is the path to fulfilling the creation mandate. <strong>Vahakimoti et-briti itchem</strong>: I will establish (<em>hekim</em>) my covenant with you — not make a new covenant but confirm/uphold the existing one. Covenant-keeping by Israel does not create the covenant; it activates its promised consequences.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>vaachaltem yashen noshan venoshan mipnei chadash totziu</strong>: you shall eat old grain long stored, and you shall clear out the old to make way for the new. The abundance is so great that old stores must be discarded to make room for new harvests. This is the blessing of superabundance — not scarcity management but generous overflow. The image requires Israel to imagine a problem of excess rather than deficit.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>venatati mishkani betochechem velo-tigal nafshi etchem</strong>: I will place my dwelling (<em>mishkan</em>) among you, and my soul shall not loathe you. <strong>Mishkan</strong> (dwelling/tabernacle, from <em>shakan</em> = to dwell/abide) — the divine dwelling among Israel is the crown of all blessings. Everything else flows from this: YHWH's presence in the midst of his people is the source of rain, harvest, peace, and victory. <strong>Lo-tigal nafshi etchem</strong> (my soul shall not reject/loathe you) — the negative formulation emphasizes the fragility of relationship: divine disgust would be the worst possible outcome, removing the presence that sustains everything.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>vehithalachti betochechem vehayiti lachem lelohim veatem tihyu-li leam</strong>: I will walk among you (<em>hithalachti</em>, hithpael of <em>halak</em> = to walk back and forth, to be present in ongoing movement) and will be your God, and you shall be my people. The covenant formula (<em>ani YHWH eloheichem</em>) in its fullest expression. <strong>Hithalachti</strong> (walking-about, being present in ongoing relational movement) echoes God walking in the garden (Gen 3:8, <em>mithalech</em> = same hithpael form) — covenant life restores Eden's intimacy. Paul quotes this verse in 2 Cor 6:16 as the basis for the church as the temple of the living God.</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>anochi YHWH eloheichem asher hotzeiti etchem meeretz mitzraim</strong>: I am YHWH your God who brought you out of the land of Egypt — the exodus-redemption warrant that grounds all covenant obligation. The covenant blessings are not offered to strangers but to those already redeemed. <strong>Vaeshbor motot ulchem vaolech etchem komemiyut</strong>: I broke the bars of your yoke and made you walk upright (<em>komemiyut</em> = erect, with dignity). <em>Komemiyut</em> appears only here — the upright posture of those freed from slavery's crouch. The Exodus is not merely release but dignity-restoration.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>ve-im lo tishmehu li</strong>: but if you do not listen to me (<em>shama</em> = to hear, to obey). The curse section begins. <strong>Shama</strong> in covenant context encompasses both hearing and responding — the Hebrew does not distinguish passive hearing from active obedience. Not-listening is not a cognitive failure but a covenantal one: refusing to respond to what is heard.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>ve-im bechukotai timasu</strong>: if you reject (<em>maas</em>) my statutes. <strong>Maas</strong> (to reject, despise, refuse) is a strong volitional term — not passive neglect but active repudiation. Paired with <strong>tikgeah nafshchem et-mishpatai</strong> (your soul abhors my judgments) — the escalation from not-listening (v14) to rejecting statutes (v15a) to the soul abhoring judgments (v15b) describes a progressive hardening of resistance. <strong>Lefru et-briti</strong> (to break my covenant) — covenant-breaking is the culmination of the sequence.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>af-ani eseh-zot lachem</strong>: then I also will do this to you — the divine af (also, indeed, even) introducing the curse sequence. <strong>Behalah</strong> (terror, sudden dread) is the first curse — psychological collapse. <strong>Shachefet</strong> (wasting disease, consumption) and <strong>qaddachat</strong> (fever, burning inflammation) — specific diseases with Mesopotamian parallels. The counterpart of covenant blessing's abundance is the withering of the body and the harvest: <strong>mazre kom zarchem larik</strong> (your sowing shall be in vain, for enemies will eat it). The same agricultural framework as the blessings, now reversed.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>venatati fanai bachem veningaftem lifnei oiveichem</strong>: I will set my face against you (<em>natati fanai bachem</em>) and you shall be struck before your enemies. The divine face, which was the source of blessing when turned toward (v9: <em>uphariti etchem</em>), becomes the source of curse when turned against. <strong>Natati panai</strong> as covenant curse is the exact reversal of the Aaronic blessing (Num 6:25: YHWH lift his face to you). The enemies who were fleeing from Israel (vv. 7-8) now become the ones before whom Israel flees.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>ve-im ad eleh lo tishmehu li</strong>: and if in spite of all this you will not listen to me, I will discipline you seven times more for your sins. The escalation structure of Lev 26 is unique in the OT: four escalating rounds of punishment, each introduced by the if-not-listen refrain. <strong>Sheva al-chatoteichem</strong> (seven times for your sins) — the sevenfold intensification is not arithmetical but signifies completeness of judgment, the full covenant curse without mitigation.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>veshavarti et-geun uzechem</strong>: I will break the pride of your power (<em>geun uzechem</em>). <strong>Gaon</strong> (pride, majesty) here refers not to sinful arrogance but to national strength and dignity — the very qualities the blessing of v13 restored (komemiyut). The breaking of this dignity is the reversal of the Exodus-dignity. <strong>Venatati et-shameichem kabarzel veet-artzchem kanechoset</strong>: I will make your heavens like iron and your earth like bronze — the sky that should give rain becomes impenetrable; the earth that should yield crops becomes hard and unyielding. The inversion of the rain-blessing (v4) as an image of covenant withdrawal.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>vetam lashav kochechem</strong>: and your strength shall be spent in vain. Agricultural effort without yield — the curse of futility. Even when Israel works, there is no result: the labor is real but the harvest is empty. This is the deep dread of the ANE farmer whose entire economy depends on productive crops. The irony is not that Israel is lazy but that diligence produces nothing under covenant curse.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>ve-im telechu imi keri</strong>: if you walk contrary to me in <strong>keri</strong>. <em>Keri</em> (from <em>qarah</em> = to meet/happen) is used uniquely in Lev 26 (vv. 21, 23, 24, 27, 28, 40, 41) — 7 occurrences in this chapter only. Its meaning is debated: chance/accident (treating covenant as random event), hostility/opposition, or stubbornness/perversity. The common denominator is treating YHWH's discipline as coincidental rather than covenantal — failing to recognize divine intention in adversity. This refusal to read history theologically is itself a sin — the sin of treating YHWH as absent or irrelevant.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>veshilachti bachem et-chayyat hasadeh</strong>: I will send wild animals against you (<em>chayyat hasadeh</em> = the beasts of the field). The reversal of the peace-blessing of v6 (harmful beasts removed). <strong>Vishikla etchem vechirita et-behemtechem vehimit'ata etchem veshamemu darkeichem</strong>: they will bereave you and destroy your livestock and make you few, and your roads will be desolate. The progressive devastation — children, livestock, population, travel routes — describes the spiral of agricultural and social collapse.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>ve-im-eleh lo tivaseiru li vhalachtem imi keri</strong>: if by these things you are not corrected but still walk contrary to me in keri. <strong>Vasar</strong> (to discipline, instruct, correct) — divine punishment is simultaneously pedagogical: the purpose of the curses is correction, not destruction. The recurrence of keri (for the third time) emphasizes that the sin being judged is not just disobedience but the refusal to recognize and respond to correction.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>vehalachti af-ani imchem bekeri vehikeiti etchem af-ani sheva al-chatoteichem</strong>: then I will walk contrary (<em>keri</em>) to you — I also — and I will strike you seven times for your sins. YHWH meets keri with keri: Israel's refusal to treat YHWH as covenantally present is met with YHWH treating Israel with the same reciprocal distance. This is the covenant's dark logic: God honors the mode of relationship Israel chooses — if Israel treats the covenant as irrelevant, YHWH acts accordingly.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>vehaveiti aleichem cherev nokat niqam brit</strong>: I will bring a sword upon you, the avenger of covenant vengeance (<em>niqam brit</em>). <strong>Niqam brit</strong> (covenant vengeance/avengement) — the sword is not arbitrary violence but the covenant's enforcement mechanism. <strong>Naqam</strong> (vengeance, retribution) in covenant context refers to the covenant's self-executing consequence clause: the curses function as stated. <strong>Dever</strong> (plague/pestilence) in the besieged cities completes the sword-and-plague combination that recurs in prophetic judgment oracles (Jer 14:12; Ezek 6:11-12).</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>beshivri lachem mateh lechem</strong>: when I break the staff of bread (<em>mateh lechem</em>) for you. <strong>Mateh</strong> (staff, rod) metaphorically describes bread as the staff that supports human life — the basis of strength and survival. Breaking the staff of bread = removing the sustaining supply. The rationing of bread by weight in a single oven is the picture of extreme scarcity — the inverse of the abundance-overflow of v10. Ten women baking for a whole household in one small oven, and the bread not satisfying.</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>ve-im bezot lo tishmehu li vehalachtem imi bekeri</strong>: if in spite of this you will not listen to me but walk contrary to me in keri — the fourth and final escalation trigger. The persistent keri, now after four rounds of escalating discipline, reaches the point of final, comprehensive judgment.</p>",
"28": "<p><strong>vehalachti imchem bachamat-keri</strong>: then I will walk with you in the fury of keri (<em>bachamat-keri</em>) — my burning anger in keri-mode. The divine keri, previously described as reciprocal detachment, now becomes charged with <strong>chemah</strong> (fury, heat, burning wrath) — the full intensity of divine judgment. This is the highest escalation in the series.</p>",
"29": "<p><strong>vaachaltem besar beneichem uvesar benoteichem tochelu</strong>: you shall eat the flesh of your sons, and the flesh of your daughters you shall eat. Cannibalism during siege — the most terrible curse imaginable in the ANE. This is not rhetorical exaggeration: the siege of Jerusalem (2 Kgs 6:28-29; Lam 4:10) records exactly this. Lamentations 4:10 quotes this horror as fulfilled reality. The reversal of the parental love that lies at the heart of social bonds represents the total collapse of covenant community into self-devouring chaos.</p>",
"30": "<p><strong>vehishmadeti et-bamoteichem</strong>: I will destroy your high places (<em>bamot</em>). <strong>Bamot</strong> (high places) — the sites of illicit worship that were the primary expression of keri (treating YHWH as one among many). <strong>Vegidate et-hammoteichem</strong>: I will cut down your incense altars (<em>chammanim</em>). <strong>Chammanim</strong> (incense stands, related to <em>chamah</em> = sun) — possibly sun-worship altars. The destruction of the worship infrastructure that replaced YHWH is itself the judgment: the objects of misplaced devotion are destroyed in the punishment for misplaced devotion. <strong>Venafonati et-pigreichem al-pigrei giluleichem</strong>: I will throw your corpses upon the corpses of your idols (<em>gilulim</em>). <strong>Gilulim</strong> (a uniquely derogatory term for idols, possibly related to <em>galal</em> = dung-balls) — a term of contempt. Israel and its idols share the same fate: corpse upon corpse.</p>",
"31": "<p><strong>venatati et-areichem chorba</strong>: I will make your cities a desolation (<em>chorbah</em>, from <em>charev</em> = to be dry, waste). <strong>Vahahsimoti et-mikdesheichem</strong>: I will make your sanctuaries desolate (<em>hashimmoti</em>). The divine abandonment of the sanctuaries — making holy places into ruins — is the extreme reversal of v11-12 (I will set my mishkan among you, I will walk among you). God removing his presence from his own house is the covenant curse's theological climax: worse than military defeat or famine is divine absence.</p>",
"32": "<p><strong>vahasimoti ani et-haaretz</strong>: and I myself (<em>ani</em> emphatic) will make the land desolate. The divine first-person emphasis underscores that the devastation is not accidental but intentional and judicial. <strong>Veshamemu aleha oiveichem</strong>: your enemies who settle in it shall be appalled at it — even the conquerors find the land so destroyed that they are horrified rather than pleased with their acquisition. The land's desolation exceeds the expectations of conquest.</p>",
"33": "<p><strong>veetchem ezareh vagoyim</strong>: and I will scatter you among the nations (<em>ezareh vagoyim</em>). <strong>Zarah</strong> (to scatter, to winnow) — the image of winnowing (separating grain from chaff by scattering in the wind) applied to Israel among the nations. <strong>Vahrikoti achareichem cherev</strong>: I will unsheathe the sword after you (<em>vahrikoti</em> = to draw out, bare). The sword pursues the scattered. <strong>Vehayetah artzechem shemamah vearekeichem yihyu chorba</strong>: your land shall be desolation and your cities shall be ruins — the land-curse expressed in its final and most complete form.</p>",
"34": "<p><strong>az tirtzeh haaretz et-shabbetoteha kol yemei hashemamah</strong>: then the land shall enjoy (<em>tirtzeh</em>, from <em>ratzah</em> = to be pleased with, to accept favorably) its Sabbaths all the days it lies desolate. The land gets the Sabbath rest it was denied when Israel worked it continuously in covenant violation. <strong>Ratzah</strong> is a key priestly term for acceptance of sacrifice (the offering being favorably received by YHWH) — here the desolate land is an offering of Sabbath rest. 2 Chronicles 36:21 cites this verse as fulfilled in the Babylonian exile: 70 years of exile for the Sabbaths the land was denied (assuming 490 years of violation).</p>",
"35": "<p><strong>kol yemei hashemamah tishbot et asher lo shavtah beshabbetoteichem beshivtechem aleha</strong>: all the days it lies desolate it shall rest — what it did not rest during your sabbatical years while you were dwelling in it. The Sabbath theology of the land (Lev 25:1-7) is here enforced retroactively by exile: the land keeps the years it was owed. This is not merely agricultural reasoning but covenant justice — YHWH ensures that the Sabbath year commands are fulfilled even if it requires removing Israel from the land to accomplish it.</p>",
"36": "<p><strong>vehannish'arim bachem vehaveti morekh bilevavam beertzot oiveichem</strong>: and as for those of you who survive, I will send faintness (<em>morekh</em> = cowardice, despair) into their hearts in the lands of their enemies. <strong>Morekh</strong> (from <em>rakah</em> = to be tender/soft/fearful) is the opposite of <em>chazaq lev</em> (strength/courage). The psychological devastation of exile — the loss of identity, the sense of divine abandonment — produces the faintheartedness described here. <strong>Venas etchem kekol aleh nidaf</strong>: they shall flee as though fleeing from a sword, though no sword pursues — paranoid flight with no objective cause, the psychological breakdown of those under covenant curse.</p>",
"37": "<p><strong>vechishot ish beauchiv kemipnei-cherev verodef ayin</strong>: they shall stumble over one another, as if to escape a sword, though none pursues. Social disintegration: the exiles trip over each other in their panic. <strong>Veloh-tihyeh lachem teqomah lifnei oiveichem</strong>: and you shall have no power to stand before your enemies. The military collapse is complete — not just defeat but inability even to take a stance. The covenant-curse has unmade the warrior nation of v7-8.</p>",
"38": "<p><strong>avadetm bagoyim vaacelah etchem eretz oiveichem</strong>: you shall perish among the nations, and the land of your enemies shall eat you up. <strong>Aved</strong> (to perish, be lost) — the scattering (v33) leads to absorption and disappearance among the nations. <strong>Tochel</strong> (to eat, consume) — the land devours its inhabitants. The verb reverses the eating of the land's produce in the blessings: instead of Israel eating the land's fruit (v10), the land of enemies eats Israel.</p>",
"39": "<p><strong>vehannish'arim bachem yimmaqequ beavonam beertzot oiveichem</strong>: and those who survive shall rot away (<em>yimmaqequ</em>, from <em>maqaq</em> = to rot, dissolve, waste away) in the iniquities of their fathers along with them they shall rot away. The exile generation inherits and shares in the consequences of their ancestors' covenant violations. This is not arbitrary: the exiles in Babylon discovered themselves implicated in the long trajectory of Israel's covenant unfaithfulness. Ezekiel addresses this explicitly (Ezek 18) — while individuals bear their own responsibility, the national consequence is multigenerational.</p>",
"40": "<p><strong>vehitvadu et-avonam veet-avon avotam</strong>: they shall confess their iniquity and the iniquity of their fathers. <strong>Yadah</strong> (hithpael = to confess, acknowledge) — voluntary, first-person acknowledgment of sin. The path out of exile begins with confession: specifically confessing <strong>maalam asher malelu bi veasher halchu imi bekeri</strong> (their treachery in which they acted faithlessly against me, and also that they walked contrary to me in keri). The keri that caused the exile must be named and acknowledged before restoration can begin. Daniel 9 and Nehemiah 1 are explicit examples of exactly this confession following exile.</p>",
"41": "<p><strong>af-ani alechem bekeri veheve'ti otam beeretz oiveichem</strong>: I also walked contrary to them in keri and brought them to the land of their enemies. The divine keri (v24, v28) is here retrospectively acknowledged as what happened: YHWH's keri-response to Israel's keri was precisely the exile. <strong>Az yikkana levavam heorel</strong>: then their uncircumcised heart shall be humbled (<em>yikkana</em>, from <em>kana</em> = to be subdued, humbled). <strong>Lev arel</strong> (uncircumcised heart) — the heart that has not been cut open by the covenant's mark. Jeremiah 4:4 and Deut 10:16; 30:6 use the same idiom: the external sign of circumcision is meant to correspond to an interior cutting-open of the heart. The exile humbles the uncircumcised heart into the confessing heart of v40.</p>",
"42": "<p><strong>vezecharti et-briti yaaqov vaf-et-briti yitzcheq vaf-et-briti avraham ezkor vehaaretz ezkor</strong>: I will remember my covenant with Jacob, and also my covenant with Isaac, and also my covenant with Abraham I will remember, and the land I will remember. The triple covenant-remembrance formula is the theological turning point of the chapter: after the full deployment of the curses, YHWH's initiative in remembering — not waiting for Israel to earn restoration — provides the basis for hope. <strong>Zakar berit</strong> (to remember the covenant) is a key theological act in Scripture (Gen 9:15; Exod 2:24; 6:5). The order is reversed (Jacob-Isaac-Abraham) — starting with the most recent, moving to the foundational. The land is remembered alongside the people: the land's restoration is part of the covenant promise.</p>",
"43": "<p><strong>vehaaretz te'azev mehem vitretzeh et-shabbetoteha beshomemah mehem</strong>: the land shall be abandoned by them and shall enjoy its Sabbaths while it lies desolate without them. The land's Sabbath-rest (v34-35) is repeated here, but now in the context of restoration hope — the Sabbath-rest of the land during exile is not only punishment but preparation, making the land ready to receive Israel again. <strong>Vehem yirtzeh et-avonam</strong>: and they shall make amends for their iniquity — <em>ratzah</em> in the hiphil sense of bearing penalty and having it accepted. The satisfaction of covenant penalty creates the condition for restoration.</p>",
"44": "<p><strong>veaf gam-zot biheyotam beeretz oiveichem lo meatiytim velo gealtim lechalotam lehafar briti itam</strong>: yet for all that, when they are in the land of their enemies, I will not spurn them or loathe them so as to destroy them utterly, to break my covenant with them. The final theological statement of the chapter: despite exile, YHWH will not make a <em>kallah</em> (complete destruction) of Israel. The double negatives (<em>lo meatiytim velo gealtim</em>) — I will not reject, I will not abhor — are the exile's last line of defense against despair. The covenant-destruction that would make Israel like the nations is what YHWH explicitly refuses. <strong>Ki ani YHWH eloheichem</strong>: for I am YHWH their God — the divine self-identification that grounds the irrevocable nature of the covenant.</p>",
"45": "<p><strong>vezecharti lahem brit rishonim</strong>: I will remember for them the covenant of the ancestors (<em>brit rishonim</em>), whom I brought out of the land of Egypt before the eyes of the nations, to be their God — I am YHWH. The covenant with the ancestors (<em>rishonim</em> = first ones, founders) — the patriarchal covenant — is the oldest and most foundational. Its remembered quality (<em>zecharti</em>) ensures that exile cannot be the final chapter: the covenant made before the nation existed cannot be unmade by the nation's failure. The Exodus-authorization (<em>asher hotzeti otam meeretz mitzraim</em>) re-grounds the covenant in the prior act of redemption that called Israel into existence.</p>",
"46": "<p><strong>eleh hachukim vehamishpatim vehatorah</strong>: these are the statutes, the rules, and the laws (<em>torah</em>). The chapter closes with a summary formula: the three legal categories — <em>chukim</em> (statutes, things inscribed by divine authority), <em>mishpatim</em> (judgments, case-law precedents), and <em>torah</em> (instruction, teaching as a whole) — together encompass the full body of covenant law delivered to Moses on Mount Sinai for the people of Israel. The formal closure identifies the entire Holiness Code (chs. 17-26) as a unified legal corpus with Sinai authority.</p>"
},
"27": {
"1": "<p>Chapter 27 is a legal appendix to the Holiness Code, addressing the commutation of dedicated persons and objects. YHWH speaks to Moses with the familiar introductory formula.</p>",
"2": "<p><strong>ish ki yafle neder beerekcha nefashot l-YHWH</strong>: when a person makes a special vow (<em>yafle neder</em>) involving persons at your valuation (<em>beerekcha</em>) to YHWH. <strong>Pala</strong> (in the hiphil: to make extraordinary, to set apart by vow) — a special/extraordinary vow as distinct from regular offerings. <strong>Erekh</strong> (valuation, assessed value) is the central term of ch. 27: the monetary value assigned to persons or things dedicated to YHWH by vow. The <em>erekh</em> system provides a mechanism for commuting the dedication of persons into money payments, allowing the person to continue normal life while fulfilling the vow financially.</p>",
"3": "<p><strong>vehayah erkecha hazachar miben esrim shanah vead ben-shishim shanah</strong>: the valuation for a male from 20 to 60 years old shall be 50 shekels of silver. The <em>erekh</em> schedule by age and gender: males 20-60 = 50 shekels. The scale reflects productive economic capacity — the peak working years carry the highest valuation. This is not a measure of human worth before God but a practical financial schedule for commuting vows in a subsistence economy.</p>",
"4": "<p><strong>ve-im neqevah hi vehayah erkecha sheloshim shoqel</strong>: if female, the valuation shall be 30 shekels. The female valuation (30 shekels, 20-60 years) reflects the economic productivity differential in an agricultural society. This is an economic assessment, not a theological statement about the equal dignity of women before God (cf. Gal 3:28 for the new covenant's transformation).</p>",
"5": "<p><strong>ve-im miben-chamesh shanim vead ben-esrim shanah</strong>: from 5 to 20 years: male 20 shekels, female 10 shekels. The reduced valuations for younger persons reflect lower economic productivity. The age-brackets (birth-1 month, 1-5 years, 5-20, 20-60, 60+) provide a comprehensive schedule covering the entire life cycle.</p>",
"6": "<p><strong>ve-im miben-chodesh vead ben-chamesh shanim vehayah erkecha hazachar chamisha sheqalim kesef</strong>: from one month to five years: male 5 shekels, female 3 shekels. The inclusion of infants (from one month) in the valuation schedule shows that the vow system covers even the dedication of newborns (cf. Hannah's dedication of Samuel, 1 Sam 1:11). The 1-month threshold corresponds to the age at which first-born sons are redeemed (Num 18:16), suggesting a connection between these systems.</p>",
"7": "<p><strong>ve-im miben-shishim shanah vamaalah im zachar</strong>: if 60 years and above: male 15 shekels, female 10 shekels. The elderly receive lower valuations — reduced economic productivity in old age. The entire schedule from birth through old age demonstrates that the vow system was designed to be comprehensive and practically workable rather than a burden that could not be met.</p>",
"8": "<p><strong>ve-im mak hu meerecha vehemido lifnei hakkohen veherimu hakkohen</strong>: if the person is too poor (<em>mak</em> = reduced, impoverished) to pay the valuation, he shall be presented before the priest, who shall assess him. <strong>Mak</strong> (from <em>muq</em> = to be dissolved, weakened, reduced) describes economic reduction below the ability to meet the standard valuation. The priest then sets a proportional amount based on what the person can afford — <strong>al pi asher tasig yad hannoder</strong> (according to what the hand of the vow-maker can reach). This income-proportional adjustment is a built-in equity mechanism: the vow system must not be so burdensome that poor Israelites cannot participate in worship.</p>",
"9": "<p><strong>ve-im behemah asher yaqrivu mimena qorban l-YHWH kol asher yitten mimena l-YHWH yihyeh qodesh</strong>: if the vow concerns livestock fit for offering to YHWH, everything given to YHWH shall be holy. <strong>Qorban</strong> (offering, from <em>qarav</em> = to bring near) — any dedicated animal becomes <em>qodesh</em> (holy/set apart) the moment it is designated for YHWH. The holiness is not achieved by the act of sacrifice but by the act of dedication.</p>",
"10": "<p><strong>lo yachaliyfenu velo yamir oto tov bera o ra betov veim hamir yamir beheimah beheimah vehayah-hu utemurato yihyeh qodesh</strong>: he shall not exchange or substitute (<em>yachaliyfenu... yamir</em>) it, good for bad or bad for good; if he should substitute one animal for another, both it and its substitute shall be holy. The anti-substitution rule protects the integrity of the dedication system: once an animal is designated for YHWH, it cannot be swapped out for a lesser animal. The attempted substitution makes both animals holy — a disincentive that discourages manipulation of the vow system.</p>",
"11": "<p><strong>ve-im kol behemah temeh asher lo yaqrivu mimena qorban l-YHWH</strong>: and if it is an unclean animal, not fit for offering to YHWH — the person shall present the animal before the priest. Unclean animals cannot be sacrificed but can still be the subject of dedication vows. The priest values them, and the person may redeem them by paying the valuation plus one-fifth (<em>chamishito</em>). The redemption-plus-fifth (20% surcharge) is a recurring feature of the ch. 27 redemption system.</p>",
"12": "<p><strong>veherimu hakkohen bein tov uvein ra</strong>: the priest shall value it between good and bad — at whatever valuation the priest sets, that it shall be. The priestly valuation authority for unclean animals is absolute: <strong>kemerkah hakkohen ken yihyeh</strong> (as the priest values it, so it shall be).</p>",
"13": "<p><strong>ve-im ga'ol yig'alenu</strong>: and if he redeems it. <strong>Ga'al</strong> (to redeem, buy back) — the key term of the Levitical redemption system. <em>Ga'al</em> in Leviticus 25-27 covers the redemption of land, persons, and dedicated property. The same root underlies <em>go'el</em> (kinsman-redeemer) — the family member with both the right and obligation to buy back what a relative has lost. The theological extension to YHWH as Israel's go'el (Isa 41:14; 44:6; 48:17) makes the redemption system a type of divine redemption.</p>",
"14": "<p><strong>ve-ish ki yaqadish et-beito qodesh l-YHWH</strong>: when a man consecrates (<em>yaqadish</em>) his house as holy to YHWH — the priest values it as good or bad, and at the priest's valuation it shall stand. Houses can be dedicated and then redeemed; the 20% surcharge applies here as well.</p>",
"15": "<p><strong>ve-im hamaqadish yigal et-beito veyasaf chamishit kesef erkecha alav vehayah lo</strong>: if the consecrator redeems his house, he shall add a fifth to the valuation price and it shall be his. The redemption-with-surcharge rule ensures that dedicating and immediately redeeming is not a zero-cost exercise: there is a cost to changing one's mind about a dedication. The surcharge incentivizes completion of vows and discourages treating dedication as a reversible financial instrument.</p>",
"16": "<p><strong>ve-im misedeh achuzzato yaqadish ish l-YHWH</strong>: if a person consecrates to YHWH part of his ancestral land (<em>sedeh achuzzato</em>). <strong>Achuzzah</strong> (possession, inherited land, from <em>achaz</em> = to hold, take possession) — the ancestral land of the tribe. The valuation of ancestral land is connected to the Jubilee: the value is calculated by the number of years remaining until the Jubilee. <strong>Zerah seor</strong> (seed of barley/homer) is the unit of measurement — 1 homer of barley seed = 50 shekels for a full 50-year Jubilee period.</p>",
"17": "<p><strong>im mishenat hayovel yaqadish sadahu keerkecha yaqum</strong>: if he consecrates his field from the Jubilee year, the full valuation applies. The land-valuation system is explicitly linked to the Jubilee (Lev 25): the closer to the next Jubilee, the less the land is worth for valuation purposes, since the buyer only has use of it until the Jubilee year when it reverts to the original family.</p>",
"18": "<p><strong>ve-im achar hayovel yaqadish sadahu</strong>: if after the Jubilee he consecrates his field. The priest calculates the proportional value: the remaining years until the next Jubilee determine the price. This is a time-value-of-money calculation built into the Torah — the principle that future possession is worth less than present possession.</p>",
"19": "<p><strong>ve-im ga'ol yig'al et-hasadeh hamaqadish oto</strong>: if he who consecrated the field redeems it — he shall add a fifth to the valuation price and it shall remain his. The redemption option with surcharge applies to land as to houses. The redemption right belongs to the original owner (or family member), consistent with the Jubilee's principle of preserving ancestral inheritance.</p>",
"20": "<p><strong>ve-im lo yig'al et-hasadeh ve-im-machar et-hasadeh le-ish acher</strong>: if he does not redeem the field, or if he has sold the field to another person — it cannot be redeemed anymore. The forfeiture-if-sold clause: if the consecrated land is sold to a third party before being redeemed, it permanently becomes temple property rather than reverting to the original family at Jubilee. This rule prevents using the consecration-and-sale sequence as a way to alienate ancestral land permanently.</p>",
"21": "<p><strong>vehayah hasadeh betzeto bayovel qodesh l-YHWH kesadeh hachereem</strong>: when the field reverts in the Jubilee, it shall be holy to YHWH like a devoted field (<em>sadeh hachereem</em>) — it becomes the priest's property. <strong>Cherem</strong> (devoted thing, irrevocable dedication) is introduced here — the category of absolute dedication that cannot be redeemed. The transition from regular consecration to cherem occurs when the normal redemption pathway is blocked.</p>",
"22": "<p><strong>ve-im et-sedeh miqnato asher lo misedeh achuzzato yaqadish l-YHWH</strong>: if he consecrates to YHWH a field that he has purchased, which is not his ancestral field. Purchased land (as opposed to ancestral inheritance) is valued differently: it belongs to the original owner at the Jubilee regardless. The valuation runs to the Jubilee year, when the field reverts to its original owner.</p>",
"23": "<p><strong>vechishuv lo hakkohen et michsat haerkcha ad shenat hayovel</strong>: the priest shall calculate for him the amount of the valuation up to the Jubilee year. The priest as financial calculator — the technical role the priesthood plays in the complex redemption-and-valuation system. The exactness of the calculation (down to specific year) reflects the systemic precision of the Jubilee framework.</p>",
"24": "<p><strong>beshenat hayovel yashov hasadeh laasher qonahu meito laasher lo achuzzat haaretz</strong>: in the Jubilee year the field shall revert to him from whom it was bought, to whom the land belongs as a possession. The Jubilee's land-restoration principle (Lev 25:13) applies even to consecrated purchased land. The purchased field cannot be permanently alienated from its original owner by consecration any more than by sale.</p>",
"25": "<p><strong>vechol-erkecha yihyeh besheqel hakodesh</strong>: all valuations shall be according to the shekel of the sanctuary (<em>sheqel hakodesh</em>). <strong>Sheqel hakodesh</strong> (sanctuary/holy shekel) — a standardized unit of weight used for temple transactions, likely equivalent to 20 gerahs. The specification of the sanctuary shekel prevents monetary manipulation through use of lighter civil shekels. The sanctuary maintains its own weight standard — a form of financial integrity built into the system.</p>",
"26": "<p><strong>ach bechor asher yevukkar l-YHWH behemah lo yaqadish ish oto</strong>: but a firstborn of animals, which belongs to YHWH as a firstborn, no one may dedicate. <strong>Bechor</strong> (firstborn) animals already belong to YHWH by right of firstborn (Exod 13:2; Num 18:15-17) — they cannot be further dedicated because they are already YHWH's. You cannot give what you do not own. This rule clarifies the scope of the vow/dedication system: only what belongs to the individual can be dedicated.</p>",
"27": "<p><strong>ve-im babeheimah hatemeah ufadah veerkecha veyasaf chamishito alav</strong>: if it is an unclean animal, he shall redeem it at the valuation price plus one-fifth, or if it is not redeemed, it shall be sold at the valuation. The consistent surcharge-for-redemption rule applied to unclean firstborn animals. The 20% surcharge appears seven times in the chapter — its recurrence establishes it as the chapter's primary financial principle.</p>",
"28": "<p><strong>ach kol-cherem asher yacherim ish l-YHWH mikol-asher-lo me-adam ubehemah umisedeh achuzzato lo yimmacer velo yigael kol-cherem qodesh qadashim hu l-YHWH</strong>: but nothing that a person devotes (<em>yacherim</em>) to YHWH as an irrevocable devotion (<em>cherem</em>), whether man, animal, or inherited field, shall be sold or redeemed. Every cherem is most holy (<em>qodesh qadashim</em>) to YHWH. <strong>Cherem</strong> (from <em>charam</em> = to devote irrevocably, to put under the ban) is the most absolute form of dedication in the OT — unlike the erekh-valuations of the rest of the chapter, which can be redeemed with a surcharge, cherem is irrevocable. The same word describes the ban on Canaanite cities (Josh 6:17-21) and the devoted spoil of war. Its irrevocability means that cherem-dedicated persons face death (v29) — the person cannot be redeemed because they have been absolutely given over to divine disposal.</p>",
"29": "<p><strong>kol-cherem asher yucherem min-haadam lo yipadeh mot yumat</strong>: no devoted person (<em>cherem min-haadam</em>) who is irrevocably devoted shall be redeemed — he shall surely be put to death. The cherem-death penalty applies to human cherem-dedications. This verse has been interpreted variously: as referring to criminals condemned by the community and devoted to God's judgment; as referring to enemy warriors under the ban; or as the logical extreme of the cherem principle where absolute devotion to YHWH means the person is no longer available for any earthly use. The NT transformation of cherem-logic: Paul's anathema (from <em>ana-thema</em> = devotion/curse) in Gal 1:8-9 invokes the same absolute-devotion language, applied to those who pervert the gospel.</p>",
"30": "<p><strong>vechol-maaser haaretz mizera haaretz mipri haaetz l-YHWH hu qodesh l-YHWH</strong>: all the tithe of the land — whether of the seed of the land or of the fruit of the trees — is YHWH's; it is holy to YHWH. <strong>Maaser</strong> (tithe, tenth, from <em>eser</em> = ten) — the tenth portion that belongs to YHWH by right of his ownership of the land (Ps 24:1). The tithe is declared <em>qodesh l-YHWH</em> (holy to YHWH) — set apart, belonging to God's domain. The tithe is not an act of generosity but a recognition of ownership: the land is YHWH's, and the tithe acknowledges this. Malachi 3:10 builds on this: robbing YHWH of the tithe is robbing him of what is already his.</p>",
"31": "<p><strong>ve-im ga'ol yig'al ish mimaaasero chamishito yosif alav</strong>: if a person redeems any of his tithe, he shall add a fifth to it. The redemption-plus-fifth rule applies to tithes as well as dedicated property: if the tithe-payer wishes to keep the actual grain or fruit and pay money instead, the 20% surcharge applies. The surcharge makes cash-commutation slightly more expensive than actual tithe-payment, preserving the integrity of the tithing system.</p>",
"32": "<p><strong>vechol-maaser baqar vatzon kol asher-yaavor tachat hashavet haasiri yihyeh-qodesh l-YHWH</strong>: and every tithe of cattle and flock, every tenth animal that passes under the staff (<em>yaavor tachat hashavet</em>) — the tenth shall be holy to YHWH. The animal tithe is calculated by counting: every animal passes under a staff or rod, and every tenth animal is automatically designated holy. The counting method (not human selection) ensures that the tithe cannot be manipulated by selecting inferior animals — the tenth passes over regardless of quality. This is the mechanical tithe, not subject to the vow-with-valuation system.</p>",
"33": "<p><strong>lo yevaqer bein tov lera velo yamiyrenu</strong>: he shall not select between good and bad or substitute for it (<em>lo yamiyrenu</em>). The non-selection, non-substitution rule for animal tithes parallels the anti-substitution rule for dedicated animals (v10). The human tendency to keep the best and give the worst is explicitly prohibited: the tenth is the tenth regardless. <strong>Ve-im hamir yamiyrenu vehayah hu utemurato yihyeh qodesh lo yigael</strong>: if he does substitute, both it and its substitute shall be holy and shall not be redeemed. The same penalty as v10: attempted manipulation results in double dedication.</p>",
"34": "<p><strong>eleh hamitzvot asher tzivah YHWH et-Moshe el-benei Yisrael behar Sinai</strong>: these are the commandments that YHWH commanded Moses for the people of Israel on Mount Sinai. The closing formula of the entire book of Leviticus — Sinai as the authoritative source of all the laws in the book, including the legal appendix of ch. 27. The Sinai-authority formula brackets Leviticus as a unified corpus of divine instruction delivered at the mountain of the covenant.</p>"
}
}

